column2: The Lìbù shàngshu oversees the Ministry of Rites responsible for religious rituals, court ceremonies, the imperial examination and China's foreign relations.
The Gongbù shàngshu is the minister responsible for the Ministry of Public Works
The Menxia shizhong is the director of the Menxia Sheng or Chancellery which advised the emperor and the Zhongshu Sheng (Central Secretariat), and reviewed edicts and commands.
The Menxia shilang is the vice-director responsible for the Menxia Sheng or Chancellery which advised the emperor and the Zhongshu Sheng (Central Secretariat), and reviewed edicts and commands.
The Tai Chang also known as Grand Master of Ceremonies, was the chief official in charge of religious rites, rituals, prayers, and the maintenance of ancestral temples and altars.

The Guang Luxun or the Supervisor of Attendants in charge of the Court of Imperial Entertainments also known as the Court of the Imperial Banquets was generally in charge of catering for the imperial household, central government officials, and imperial banquets honoring foreign envoys and other dignitaries.
The Zongzheng or Minister of the Imperial Clan was responsible for all matters pertaining to the imperial family.

The Taipu or Minister Coachman was in charge of the  Court of the Imperial Stud responsible for managing state horse pasturage, stables and corrals, as well as maintaining the vehicles for use by the imperial household and members of the central government.
The Shaofu or Minister Steward was in charge of the Court of the Imperial Treasury.
The Weiwei or Minister of the Guards was in charge of the Court of the Imperial Regalia.
The Dahonglu or Minister Herald was in charge of the Court of State Ceremonies.
The Dasinong or Minister of Finance was in charge of the Court of the National Granaries.

The Tingwei or Minister of Justice was in charge of Court of Judicature and Revision responsible for reviewing judicial proceedings at all administrative levels and singling out the cases for a retrial by court officials or the emperor himself.
The Dushuijian is the responsible for the Directorate of Waterways.
The Shaofujian is the responsible for the Directorate for Imperial Manufactories.
The Jiangzuojian is the responsible for the Directorate for Palace Buildings.
The Junqijian is the responsible for the Directorate for Armaments.
The Changqiujian is the responsible for the Directorate of Palace Domestic Service.
The Quozijian is the responsible for the Directorate of Education.
The Sitianjian is the responsible for the Directorate of Astronomy.

The Shàngshu ling or Minister of the Left was the head of the Department of State Affairs which was the primary executive institution of Imperial China, head of the Six Ministries, the Nine Courts, and the Three Directorates (sometimes five).

Shàngshu puye or Minister of the Right was the vice-director of the Department of State Affairs which was the primary executive institution of Imperial China, head of the Six Ministries, the Nine Courts, and the Three Directorates (sometimes five).

The Diànzhong shìyùshi or In-palace Enquiry Censors were officers of the the Palace Branch of the Censorate responsible for monitoring the behavior of officials during audiences. It was staffed by in-palace enquiry censors.

The Shìyùshi or Enquiry Censors were officers of the Admonishment Branch of the Censorate responsible for monitoring the behavior of the emperor, to ensure that he did not make mistakes and remind him of his duties.

The Chá Yuàn or Monitor Censors were officers of the Detection Branch of the Censorate responsible for monitoring the behavior of local officials. They would would tour the country in circuits to ensure the proper discharge of the functions of government and good performance of local officials.

The Shàngshucheng Ling or Councillor of the Left was one of the high ranking officials of the Department of State Affairs which was the primary executive institution of Imperial China, head of the Six Ministries, the Nine Courts, and the Three Directorates (sometimes five).

The Shàngshucheng Puye or Councillor of the Right was of the high ranking officials of the Department of State Affairs which was the primary executive institution of Imperial China, head of the Six Ministries, the Nine Courts, and the Three Directorates (sometimes five).

Confucius was a Chinese philosopher and politician of the Spring and Autumn period who is traditionally considered the paragon of Chinese sages.His teachings and philosophy underpin East Asian culture and society, remaining influential across China and East Asia to this day.

Laozi was an ancient Chinese philosopher and writer. He is the reputed author of the Tao Te Ching, the founder of philosophical Taoism, and a deity in religious Taoism and traditional Chinese religions.

Neo-Confucianism is a social and ethical philosophy using metaphysical ideas, some borrowed from Taoism and Buddhism, as its framework. The philosophy can be characterized as humanistic and rationalistic, with the belief that the universe could be understood through human reason, and that it was up to humanity to create a harmonious relationship between the universe and the individual.
Zhengyi or  Way of Orthodox Unity was founded by Zhang Taoling, who said that Laozi appeared to him in the year 142

Quanzhen or Completion of Authenticity was founded by Wang Chongyang and places particular emphasis on celibacy, which its adepts are expected to adhere to, and self-cultivation. Quanzhen disciple are expected to meditate on alchemical (Neidan) poems until reaching enlightenment. They do this in a cell to help sever ties to the mundane world.

Shangqing or Supreme Clarity was founded by Wei Huacun and values meditation techniques of visualization and breathing, as well as physical exercises, as opposed to the use of alchemy and talismans. The recitation of the sacred canon plays an equally important role.
Tiantai is an East Asian Buddhist school of Mahayana Buddhism that developed in 6th-century China that emphasizes the Lotus Sutra.

The Huayan worldview is based primarily on the Avatamsaka Sutra as well as on the works of the Huayan patriarchs, like Fazang.[1] The name Flower Garland is meant to suggest the crowning glory of a Buddha's profound understanding of ultimate reality.
Jingtuzong or Amidism is a broad branch of Mahayana Buddhism focused on achieving rebirth in a Buddha-field or Pure Land.

Chan Buddhism is a major Chinese Buddhist sect attributed to Bodhidharma that emphasizes attaining Buddhahood, the supreme Buddhist religious goal, through enlightenment of one's own mind, which subsequently spreaded to Japan and named as Zen
There are several competing belief systems in China that often form synchretic relationships with eachother and with traditional folk belief. Which one should we follow?
